>In your own words, explain single-page applications and progressive web apps. \
\
A: Single-age applications (SPAs) are web applications that don\'92t require page loads when navigating between pages (most websites do require this). It is basically a single page application that only has one page! When using a SPA, the page does not fully reload as only the new data gets sent over while the user navigates through the application. After an initial page load, only the data that gets requested from the server (or sent to the server) gets sent over the network. Only data gets sent over, which decreases the time and bandwidth compared to constantly sending HTML. \
\
Progressive web apps (PWAs) help speed up development time. They are applications that load fast even when on a flaky network. Progressive web apps are experiences that combine the web and apps together. As the user builds a better relationship with the app over time (with more use), the user experience gets better. It sends relevant push notifications and loads as a full screen experience. \
